WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.840
Hi, my name is Emily Riederer, and for years I've been coming to different data science conferences

00:00:05.840 --> 00:00:11.280
and telling stories about working in R. And inevitably at the end of every single session,

00:00:11.280 --> 00:00:17.120
someone would raise their hand and ask the standard question, that's great, but why didn't

00:00:17.120 --> 00:00:23.040
you use Python? And this happened to me so many times with so much regularity, I felt like I had

00:00:23.040 --> 00:00:28.639
some pretty good answers by the end. I talk about how the tidyverse is unparalleled for data wrangling,

00:00:28.639 --> 00:00:34.400
how R Markdown was just perfect for data science communication, and how R just had easier on your

00:00:34.400 --> 00:00:40.400
app for non-developers. But despite all those, like, specifics I tried to fill out, the honest

00:00:40.400 --> 00:00:45.840
answer was I just loved that magical flow state feeling of working in R, where I knew exactly what

00:00:45.840 --> 00:00:51.119
I wanted to do, and it just worked. And I didn't feel like I could ever get that with what I thought

00:00:51.119 --> 00:00:57.119
was this stack that I had to use in Python of pandas, matplotlib, and Jupyter note. It just

00:00:57.119 --> 00:01:02.639
didn't feel as organic to me. I felt like I had to make this choice between the workflow and the

00:01:02.639 --> 00:01:08.559
ergonomics that I loved in one language, and the tools that constituted a successful Python

00:01:08.559 --> 00:01:14.480
programmer in another. But instead of seeing these two things as in conflict with each other,

00:01:14.480 --> 00:01:20.000
what I've realized in the past couple of years as the stack has evolved, is that actually,

00:01:20.000 --> 00:01:24.720
these are just the criteria for picking good Python tools, and two sides of the same coin.

00:01:25.360 --> 00:01:30.959
We can find tools that both have the similar workflow we love in R, with functional programming,

00:01:30.959 --> 00:01:37.040
and a really comfortable level of abstraction, and we can use tools that are well adopted by the

00:01:37.040 --> 00:01:42.400
Python community, have that same level of support and engagement and interoperability, with plenty

00:01:42.400 --> 00:01:48.720
of questions and support on Stack Overflow and GitHub, that make us competent Python programmers

00:01:48.800 --> 00:01:52.480
without giving up everything we know and love and have learned about R.

00:01:53.839 --> 00:01:59.199
So, today, I wanted to take you through a tour of some of the tools in my ergonomic stack of

00:01:59.199 --> 00:02:04.879
working with Python, spanning aspects of that wrangling, communication, and developer tool

00:02:04.879 --> 00:02:12.160
cycle that I talked about and always ceased to claim was impossible. And to do this, in honor

00:02:12.160 --> 00:02:17.199
of this conference being hosted in Seattle, we'll use some daily weather and temperature data

00:02:17.759 --> 00:02:24.639
from Seattle. So, first, let's talk about data exploration, which is one area where many of

00:02:24.639 --> 00:02:30.639
us R users coming from a tinyverse background have really been spoiled with dplyr and ggplot2.

00:02:32.160 --> 00:02:36.800
While many think of pandas as the go-to data wrangling language, I've actually found that

00:02:36.800 --> 00:02:42.639
Polar's checks many more of the boxes for me of an ergonomic tool. We have that similar workflow

00:02:42.639 --> 00:02:47.119
with a functional paradigm and this really expressive and expansive rich API,

00:02:47.679 --> 00:02:52.080
but it isn't on its own a very stand alone impressive and successful project.

00:02:52.080 --> 00:02:58.240
It's seen great adoption in the Python community, so much so that it's natively supported in Seaborn

00:02:58.240 --> 00:03:02.559
and Scikit-learn, and there are those signals with the communities really latching on to it.

00:03:02.559 --> 00:03:08.320
And it's no wonder why. It's zero dependencies and written in ultra fast, highly performant Rust

00:03:08.320 --> 00:03:14.399
code. Looking at a surface level, I think it's clear to see some of the superficial similarities

00:03:14.399 --> 00:03:19.759
between dplyr and Polar's just in the way that it provides data frame in, data frame out methods

00:03:19.759 --> 00:03:27.520
with similar kind of function names. And beyond those naming conventions, the feature parity is

00:03:27.520 --> 00:03:33.360
also very similar, not only to dplyr, but also to the broader tidyverse. So, we have nice functions

00:03:33.360 --> 00:03:39.279
to support things like string and date wrangling, restructuring and reshaping our data, and working

00:03:39.279 --> 00:03:45.839
iteratively. But a lot of different tools can have feature parity without having that same feel,

00:03:45.839 --> 00:03:51.520
without having the ergonomics. So, what I want to do is go a little bit deeper. We can look at the

00:03:51.520 --> 00:03:57.600
actual official tidyverse design principles and see how well those stack up in Polar's. We can

00:03:57.600 --> 00:04:03.279
think about how our dplyr tools are composable. We have these small atomic functions that allow

00:04:03.279 --> 00:04:09.839
us to express really complex tasks. They're also consistent. So, the API that we learn in one

00:04:09.839 --> 00:04:15.520
package and one function easily transports and expands our knowledge across other tools. And

00:04:15.520 --> 00:04:19.839
they're human centered. They always kind of know what we're going for and kind of help us do that

00:04:19.839 --> 00:04:27.040
super easily. So, let's see how well these hold up in Polar's. In dplyr, of course, we have our

00:04:27.040 --> 00:04:31.440
piping and those data frame in and data frame out methods that make things very composable.

00:04:32.399 --> 00:04:37.279
Really across Python with method training, you can achieve that similar sort of narrative flow

00:04:37.279 --> 00:04:43.040
where we can read our code top down in the exact order of execution. Now, in R, there's no reason

00:04:43.040 --> 00:04:48.559
that we couldn't keep that piping paradigm going within each function. But our coding get kind of

00:04:48.559 --> 00:04:53.760
long and lengthy and we don't tend to do that. Instead, we tend to go back to that traditional

00:04:53.760 --> 00:04:59.519
nested function paradigm. But with Polar's, because we have a lot of nice methods to operate

00:04:59.519 --> 00:05:05.040
on individual columns, we can actually expand that sense of composability and make our code

00:05:05.040 --> 00:05:12.000
just as readable from left to right as it is from top to bottom. Similarly, in dplyr, I always value

00:05:12.000 --> 00:05:17.440
the consistency both for the purposes of reading and writing. All of the functions look sort of

00:05:17.440 --> 00:05:22.959
similar whether we're adding new columns or subsetting rows or columns. So, it's just easy

00:05:22.959 --> 00:05:28.320
both to read and to write. I never found the same to be as true about pandas where to do those same

00:05:28.399 --> 00:05:33.760
three operations, you might have to use three very different mindsets. So, using an anonymous

00:05:33.760 --> 00:05:39.519
function to alter a column. Then articulating how you want to subset your data with a string.

00:05:39.519 --> 00:05:44.320
And then just using bracket notation. It just didn't feel organic. It didn't feel like language.

00:05:45.200 --> 00:05:52.160
But again, Polar's really brings back the same kind of consistency to the language as dplyr with

00:05:52.160 --> 00:05:59.760
a lot of just very readable code. And finally, the human centeredness. dplyr spoils us with so

00:05:59.760 --> 00:06:05.279
much syntactic sugar and I feel like Polar's is very the same in this regard as well. Just one

00:06:05.279 --> 00:06:12.880
example I'll point to here is Polar's implementing select helpers which lets us easily, much like in

00:06:12.880 --> 00:06:19.600
R, identify variables by a part of a variable name or a variable type and apply the same

00:06:19.600 --> 00:06:23.679
transformation to all of those variables at once instead of duplicating our code.

00:06:25.040 --> 00:06:29.519
Similarly, Polar's also knows that as data scientists, we work with data of very different

00:06:29.519 --> 00:06:35.040
sizes and in very different places. So, whether we're reading data in batch or streaming, in memory

00:06:35.040 --> 00:06:41.359
or out of memory, we can run roughly the same Python code and let Polar's handle the details

00:06:41.359 --> 00:06:47.760
of optimizing that workflow for us. But of course, data wrangling is only one half of exploration.

00:06:47.760 --> 00:06:52.079
We also have visualization and here we actually now have two really great options.

00:06:52.640 --> 00:06:58.239
First, there's plot 9 which is a very high fidelity code clone of ggplot that is well

00:06:58.239 --> 00:07:03.119
supported by Posit. Sometimes I worry a little bit about a lot of packages that try to clone

00:07:03.119 --> 00:07:07.359
existing packages, that they may not be well supported, they may be hobby projects,

00:07:07.920 --> 00:07:13.600
but having that institutional support is huge. On the other hand, we have Seaborn objects

00:07:13.600 --> 00:07:19.760
which lives inside Seaborn, one of the most popular Python packages for data visualization,

00:07:20.320 --> 00:07:25.040
and this provides a novel experimental object-oriented programming interface

00:07:25.040 --> 00:07:31.839
with unique ggplot2 inspirations that allows us an alternative way to bring the grammar of graphics

00:07:31.839 --> 00:07:39.760
into creating the underlying matplotlib figure specifications. So, again, if we think about

00:07:39.760 --> 00:07:45.600
what makes ggplot2 special, we have that sense of a grammar mapping different components in our data

00:07:45.600 --> 00:07:50.799
to different aesthetic elements and doing that incrementally in layers where we can control each

00:07:50.799 --> 00:07:56.160
layer as much as we want. It shouldn't be hard to convince you that we can achieve that thing

00:07:56.160 --> 00:08:01.519
in plot 9 because this plot 9 code, believe it or not, is actually Python code, even though it

00:08:01.519 --> 00:08:07.440
looks almost identical to the ggplot2 code that we know and love. But if we want, we can get a

00:08:07.440 --> 00:08:12.399
little more creative and give that a little bit of its own Pythonic flavor. Using Python's

00:08:12.399 --> 00:08:17.279
incremental addition operator, we can still use all the same ggplot2 functions we know,

00:08:17.920 --> 00:08:22.880
but break our code up a little bit more without that method chaining to make it easier to debug

00:08:22.880 --> 00:08:29.679
and experiment with. Now, if we switch over to Seaborn objects, we will have slightly different

00:08:29.679 --> 00:08:35.760
syntax, but you can see largely the same design philosophy. We're still creating that plot object

00:08:35.760 --> 00:08:41.200
and incrementally adding to it and building from it, adding in geometries, altering our scales and

00:08:41.200 --> 00:08:47.599
our labels, all in that same sense of a grammar. And of course, packages that aren't clones can

00:08:47.599 --> 00:08:52.159
also be fun because they can bring new and different inspirations as well. One thing that

00:08:52.159 --> 00:08:57.760
can be hard in ggplot2, if you've ever tried, is to make facets that represent different variables

00:08:57.760 --> 00:09:02.640
in different facets. To do this, you have to kind of like manually reshape your data and almost try

00:09:02.640 --> 00:09:09.280
to trick ggplot2 into doing what you want. But Seaborn objects sort of meet this need by letting

00:09:09.280 --> 00:09:14.799
us specify multiple Y or X variables that we can put in different facets, which is a kind of fun

00:09:14.799 --> 00:09:22.159
feature. And always, any of these tools, you always worry, what if I reach the limit of this tool?

00:09:22.159 --> 00:09:26.559
Will I get kind of stuck and stranded if I'm using a tool that isn't the language standard?

00:09:27.119 --> 00:09:32.559
But both of these tools make it really easy to get out that underlying matplotlib figure. So,

00:09:32.559 --> 00:09:37.840
if we need to customize further, we can always fill up our sleeves and do so. We'll never get

00:09:37.840 --> 00:09:44.719
stranded. So, now let's talk about reproducible reporting. In R, we've always been really spoiled

00:09:44.719 --> 00:09:50.159
with having R Markdown as a way to do it. And I used to always tell people, if Python ever had

00:09:50.159 --> 00:09:56.000
anything as good as R Markdown, I'd switch over. And don't say that if you don't mean that. Because

00:09:56.000 --> 00:10:02.320
then Posit goes and creates something like Quarto. And we've already seen today all of the

00:10:02.320 --> 00:10:08.159
great sense of the last mile of what Quarto can do and all the different formats it can produce.

00:10:08.159 --> 00:10:12.479
But I'm also interested in the first mile of Quarto and the way that it can really replace

00:10:12.479 --> 00:10:17.919
Jupyter Notebook. Jupyter Notebook can be a really powerful tool for using Python,

00:10:17.919 --> 00:10:23.359
but they come with certain downsides. Their kind of rich text format can be harder to version

00:10:23.359 --> 00:10:29.280
control and peer review. Because there's a lot underlying the actual code and its representation.

00:10:30.159 --> 00:10:35.200
And because of that, you can also run into issues with managing the kernels behind it

00:10:35.200 --> 00:10:39.679
and the state of one of the different code chunks per execute. Quarto, I feel like,

00:10:39.679 --> 00:10:45.440
actually hits really nice balance for this instead of giving us a simple plain text file

00:10:45.440 --> 00:10:51.200
that we can work with and edit and save. And delivering a similarly interactive experience

00:10:51.280 --> 00:10:55.520
instead of through the file itself, but through its interactions and extensions

00:10:55.520 --> 00:11:03.679
with various IDEs, be that Positron, VS Code, or RStudio. So that's only the means of communication,

00:11:03.679 --> 00:11:09.280
but what about the substance of that communication? And for that, we have the great tables package,

00:11:09.280 --> 00:11:13.679
which you may have seen in the table session yesterday. And I would compare that to other

00:11:13.679 --> 00:11:19.679
Python equivalents, but as far as I can tell, there barely are any. Great tables is kind of

00:11:19.679 --> 00:11:25.679
unread. It's built by the same team that built the GT package in R, but curiously,

00:11:25.679 --> 00:11:30.640
they didn't even attempt to clone the syntax, but rather deliver kind of the best experience

00:11:31.200 --> 00:11:37.280
for either language independently. And you can see why I won't go into this code in great detail.

00:11:37.280 --> 00:11:41.679
We have that same sense of grammar and incrementally building up that table

00:11:41.679 --> 00:11:47.520
object piece by piece as we do on the plotting side for excellent data science.

00:11:49.760 --> 00:11:53.200
So, if any of this has interested you at all, you're probably wondering,

00:11:53.200 --> 00:11:57.919
how do I get started? And that's where we get to talk about the developer experience.

00:11:58.719 --> 00:12:05.039
In R, we've always been really spoiled by tools like RStudio for just everyday code writing and

00:12:05.039 --> 00:12:10.239
use this, which has helped us kind of bridge the gap from user to R package developer.

00:12:11.200 --> 00:12:17.039
In a very batteries included way. But then when we move to Python, there are a lot more just like

00:12:17.039 --> 00:12:22.239
small little places that can trip us up or just give us paper cuts in our work. Whether that just

00:12:22.239 --> 00:12:27.359
be installing and managing many different versions of Python, then moving to installing and managing

00:12:27.359 --> 00:12:32.239
many different packages and making sure we have the right package version in the right place.

00:12:32.239 --> 00:12:37.840
And even picking a dependency manager, of which there are 20,000 options. And finally,

00:12:37.840 --> 00:12:42.080
finding just like picking our development environment where we want to run all that code.

00:12:42.960 --> 00:12:48.799
And I think some of the ergonomics that Python's really taught us to value in terms of those

00:12:48.799 --> 00:12:55.119
IDEs are being able to do things programmatically instead of navigating through complicated UIs.

00:12:55.840 --> 00:13:01.119
Being helpful and slightly opinionated to nudge us towards good practices without being overbearing.

00:13:02.000 --> 00:13:06.159
And just being unsurprising and not having weird and unexpected sightings.

00:13:06.400 --> 00:13:11.679
So, some tools I've learned to love in this regard for Python.

00:13:12.640 --> 00:13:18.320
Our first, pyenv, which provides a great streamlined way to install Python on your system.

00:13:19.359 --> 00:13:25.679
This allows a way a structured way to install all of our different Python versions in a shared

00:13:25.679 --> 00:13:31.440
location on our computer where both we and more importantly our computer can find them again.

00:13:32.080 --> 00:13:36.400
And if you want to switch what version of Python you're actively using at either the

00:13:36.400 --> 00:13:42.000
global or the project specific level, that can also be easily done on the command line.

00:13:44.239 --> 00:13:49.840
Next up, we need to manage the different versions of different packages that we're installing for

00:13:49.840 --> 00:13:56.000
use in different projects. While environment management is a great practice in any tool,

00:13:56.000 --> 00:14:02.960
it's especially important in Python, even more so than R, because PyPy, unlike CRAN,

00:14:02.960 --> 00:14:08.320
isn't forcing us to do a lot of reverse dependency checks when new issues of packages are released.

00:14:08.320 --> 00:14:11.520
So, we're more likely to have package versioning conflicts,

00:14:11.520 --> 00:14:14.880
bubble up and immediately cause breaking changes in our code.

00:14:15.599 --> 00:14:19.119
And there are many, many different tools for creating these virtual environments.

00:14:19.919 --> 00:14:26.400
But one that I've particularly come to love is PDF, because it does exactly what I want it to do

00:14:26.400 --> 00:14:32.559
very simply and very easily and truly absolutely nothing more. It creates a virtual environment

00:14:32.559 --> 00:14:38.880
at the project level and always ensures then that we're installing the packages we want

00:14:38.880 --> 00:14:43.679
into that virtual environment instead of somewhere else. And when it does that,

00:14:43.760 --> 00:14:48.400
it logs both the dependency that we explicitly added and the dependency

00:14:48.400 --> 00:14:53.359
of those dependencies separately. This may seem like a kind of esoteric point,

00:14:53.919 --> 00:14:57.840
but it's actually really nice then if you decide you didn't need a certain dependency,

00:14:57.840 --> 00:15:03.679
because you can very cleanly uninstall both that dependency and all the access that it

00:15:03.679 --> 00:15:09.280
added to your environment altogether. And I tend to try to avoid tools that are too much

00:15:09.280 --> 00:15:14.640
off the beaten path, but one reason that I get comfortable using PDM is it's made

00:15:14.640 --> 00:15:20.320
itself very interoperable. If we want to in a single command, we can create that more common

00:15:20.320 --> 00:15:26.880
Python requirements.txt file to go ahead and reinstall and recreate that same environment

00:15:26.880 --> 00:15:32.559
with any range of other tools that maybe your coworkers or other developers might want to

00:15:32.719 --> 00:15:40.719
use. So, finally, let's talk about where we run code. VS Code is one, you know, kind of

00:15:40.719 --> 00:15:45.679
very common tool for developing in Python, which I'd really started to learn to love

00:15:45.679 --> 00:15:51.599
when Positron came along. And I think Positron is an exciting addition, largely because it just

00:15:51.599 --> 00:15:56.880
comes with a little bit more batteries included and smooths the gap of getting started and getting

00:15:56.880 --> 00:16:01.919
all those languages to talk to one another. And it brings back a lot of the features we've learned

00:16:01.919 --> 00:16:07.520
we really love from RStudio, like that plot viewer and variable explorer for very data native

00:16:07.520 --> 00:16:14.159
first environment. But the thing that's most rich about either of these tools is the ecosystem of

00:16:14.159 --> 00:16:20.719
extensions and command line tools that play nicely with them. And I think it can be easy to assume

00:16:20.719 --> 00:16:26.159
that some of these tools are kind of, oh, they're more for power users. But I truly think that's

00:16:26.159 --> 00:16:31.039
the wrong mentality. When we're starting a new language where we don't have that inherent sense

00:16:31.039 --> 00:16:36.880
of flow and intuition, some of these tools can help outsource what the back of our mind isn't

00:16:36.880 --> 00:16:43.440
giving us automatically and automate that to bring those intuitions to us. So, for example, we can

00:16:43.440 --> 00:16:48.880
use cookie cutter to create project templates and learn from many, many experienced Python

00:16:48.880 --> 00:16:54.320
developers over time who thought systemically about how to set up a good project. Similarly,

00:16:54.320 --> 00:17:00.479
we can avoid typos that newbies tend to make with tools like autodoc and pyindent to automatically

00:17:00.479 --> 00:17:04.800
create the documentation strings we need and make sure we have the right white space in our code.

00:17:05.920 --> 00:17:11.680
And then some of my favorites are error lens and rough, which provide linters and stylers

00:17:11.680 --> 00:17:18.880
to help us identify both syntactic and stylistic issues in our code and elevate them right to the

00:17:18.880 --> 00:17:24.479
front of our attention so we know to fix them. This is just one example of those packages at work

00:17:24.479 --> 00:17:29.599
that, again, as inexperienced developers, we might immediately know that some of these things

00:17:29.599 --> 00:17:35.040
are code smells or look a little fun. Like importing a package halfway through our code.

00:17:35.040 --> 00:17:40.400
Or importing a package with a typo in it. But when you're new to a language and you're juggling a lot

00:17:40.400 --> 00:17:46.319
of competing interests, you may not exactly you may not have back of your head just immediately

00:17:46.319 --> 00:17:51.199
flagging to you that those are issues. So, it's really nice to have your IDE doing it for you.

00:17:51.199 --> 00:18:00.560
So, in conclusion, I'll never be that person sitting in the front of the room asking you why

00:18:00.560 --> 00:18:07.359
you didn't use Python. R was my first love. And R is also a lot easier to make puns with. Like

00:18:07.359 --> 00:18:15.839
ergonomics. But hopefully at the end of the day, if I've done my job here correctly, you may ask

00:18:16.800 --> 00:18:22.319
why don't I also check out some of these Python tools? So, thank you very much for coming.

00:18:22.880 --> 00:18:27.920
That really concludes my talk. I'll note I do have a few related blog posts on the issue.

00:18:27.920 --> 00:18:32.239
And if you have other Python tools that you find work particularly well in your workflows,

00:18:32.239 --> 00:18:38.319
I would love to hear about them. Thank you.

